l, demonstrating its many crucial connecions to literature, popular culture, and visual culture of the time, as well as its long "afterlife" in more recent films, television, and music videos. Together, these essays make clear that Méliès was not only a major filmmaker but also a key figure in the emergence of modern spectacle and the birth of the modern cinematic imagination, and by bringing interdisciplinary methodologies of early cinema studies to bear on A Trip to the Moon, the contributors also open up much larger questions about aesthetics, media, and modernity.In his introduction, Matthew Solomon traces the convoluted provenance of the film's multiple versions and its key place in the historiography of cinema, and an appendix contains a useful dossier of primary-source documents that contextualize the film's production, along with translations of two major articles written by Méliès himself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMotion pictures. 0aMéliès, Georges, -- 1861-1938 -- Criticism and interpretation. 4aCultural Studies : Popular Culture. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aAbel, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristie, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCosta, Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuckett, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaudreault, ANDRé, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGunning, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKessler, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLefebvre, Thierry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v